|< 𝟔 >| 𝐔𝐧𝐚𝐫𝐲 𝐎𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐨𝐫 <|>
         >> Unary operators work on a single operand and perform operations 
         >> such as incrementing, decrementing, negating, or inverting a value. 

      a = 5; //for all example
   _____________________________________________________________________________
   | 𝐎𝐩𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐨𝐫 |><|        𝐃𝐞𝐬𝐜𝐫𝐢𝐩𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧        |><|  𝐄𝐱𝐚𝐦𝐩𝐥𝐞 |><|  𝐄𝐪𝐮𝐢𝐯𝐚𝐥𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐭𝐨  |
   |"""""""""""|""""""""""""""""""""""""""""""|"""""""""""""|""""""""""""""""""|
   |     +     | Unary plus (positive value)  |     +a      |      a = 5       |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
   |     -     | Unary minus (negative value) |     -a      |      a = -5      |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
   |    ++     |    Increment (pre/post)      |  ++a , a++  |      a = 6       |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
   |    --     | 	  Decrement (pre/post)      |  --a , a--  |      a = 4       |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
   |    !      |     Logical complement       |     !a      |   !true = false  |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
   |    ~      |     Bitwise complement       |     ~a      |      a = -6      |
   |-----------|------------------------------|-------------|------------------| 
   |'''''''''''|''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''|'''''''''''''|''''''''''''''''''|

